      "id": 68261,
      "name": "usolar",
      "username": "usolar",
      "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/u/e79b87/{size}.png",
      "created_at": "2025-01-15T04:59:31.471Z",
      "cooked": "<p>In the past days I did some troubleshooting. It turns out the error was riding in the big front chainring.</p>\n<p><strong>Explanation</strong><br>\nBy chance, I came across a Lama Lab video mentioning that the bigger gear increases inertia by allot, making it harder for the trainer to stabilize power (Goolge it)</p>\n<p><strong>Solution</strong><br>\nAfter switching to the smaller front chainring, my readings became much smoother and more consistent <img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/images/emoji/twitter/chart_with_upwards_trend.png?v=12\" title=\":chart_with_upwards_trend:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":chart_with_upwards_trend:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\"></p>\n<p>I admit I prefer the feel of the bigger gear, but this change made a huge difference in data stability.</p>\n<p>So if you\u2019re also experiencing similar power spikes or fluctuations, give the smaller chainring a try, it worked wonders for me!</p>\n<p><strong>Happy training, everyone! <img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/images/emoji/twitter/mountain_biking_man.png?v=12\" title=\":mountain_biking_man:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":mountain_biking_man:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\"></strong></p>",
